  "prompt": "How accurate are Credit Karma credit scores relative to the 3 main bureaus? Is Credit Karma posting hard hits on my credit report? Does monitoring my credit continuously (weekly or daily even) there harm my credit?",
  "response": "Credit Karma provides credit scores that are based on the VantageScore 3.0 model, using data from two of the three major credit bureaus: TransUnion and Equifax. While these scores can give you a good general sense of your credit health, they may not exactly match the FICO scores that are commonly used by lenders. The reason is that there are different scoring models and lenders might use their own versions of these models.\n\nAs for \"hard hits\" or \"hard inquiries,\" Credit Karma itself does not post these to your report. Checking your credit scores on Credit Karma is considered a \"soft inquiry,\" which does not affect your credit score. Hard inquiries, on the other hand, occur when a lender checks your credit report because you have applied for credit, and can impact your credit score.\n\nMonitoring your credit frequently, whether weekly or even daily, through services like Credit Karma will not harm your credit score. Since these checks are soft inquiries, they do not have any negative impact. Regular monitoring is beneficial as it helps you stay informed about your credit status and can alert you to any potential issues like identity theft.",
